First I would suggest that you follow Java naming conventions (Class names are capitalized).

A fxml file is used only to display the data and is more or less static. The controller that you appoint to this `Stage` (fxml) is responsible for DB calls or other changes.

What you are trying to do is display the data from your DB on your UI and it is pretty straightforward.

First start by implementing a class that takes care of your DB calls. It should contain (at least) two functions. One to fetch all courses that returns a `List&lt;Course&gt;` so that you can use directly that on your UI. And another one that fetches courses based on a `keyword` that a user gives.

At the moment that your stage is initialized in your controller you should fetch all your courses and display them like this:

```java
@FXML
public void initialize()
{
    YourDatabaseHandler dbHandler = new YourDatabaseHandler();
	
	List&lt;Course&gt; courses = dbHandler.getAllCourses();
	
	listViewOfCourses.getItems().addAll(courses); // ListViewOfCourses should be the listview that you have on your fxml file or controller.
}
```

Then you should add a listener to your search button. Every time the button is clicke, you fetch the filtered content from your DB through the keyword. Here is an example:

```java
@FXML
public void onSearchButtonClicked()// Here either ActionEvent or ClickEvent
{
    YourDatabaseHandler dbHandler = new YourDatabaseHandler();
    String keyword = yourTextField.getText(); // yourTextField should be the search text field
	
	List&lt;Course&gt; courses = dbHandler.getFilteredCourses(keyword);
	
    listViewOfCourses.getItems().clear(); // Remove already added courses
	listViewOfCourses.getItems().addAll(courses); // ListViewOfCourses should be the listview that you have on your fxml file or controller.
}
```

